A '''dropleton''' or '''quantum droplet''' is a [[quasiparticle]] comprising a collection of [[electron]]s and [[electron hole|holes]] inside a [[semiconductor]]. Dropletons give the first known quasiparticle characterization where the quasiparticle behaves like a liquid.<ref name="sa">{{cite web | url =http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/dropleton-quantum-droplet-quasiparticle/| title =Meet the Dropleton—a "Quantum Droplet" That Acts Like a Liquid |publisher =''[[Scientific American]]''|author=Clara Moskowitz|date=26 February 2014| accessdate =26 February 2014}}</ref> The creation of dropletons was announced on 26 February 2014 in a ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' article, which presented evidence for the creation of dropletons in an [[electron hole|electron–hole]] [[plasma (physics)|plasma]] inside a [[gallium arsenide]] [[quantum well]] by ultrashort [[laser]] pulses.<ref>{{cite journal | url =http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v506/n7489/full/nature12994.html| title =Quantum droplets of electrons and holes |author= A. E. Almand-Hunter |author2= H. Li |author3= S. T. Cundiff |author4= M. Mootz |author5= M. Kira |author6= S. W. Koch |last-author-amp= yes|publisher =''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''|date=26 February 2014| accessdate =26 February 2014|doi=10.1038/nature12994 |bibcode = 2014Natur.506..471A }}</ref> Their existence was not predicted before the experiment.
Despite the relatively short lifetime of about 25 [[picosecond]]s, the dropletons are stable enough to be studied<ref name="sa"/> and possess favorable properties for certain investigations of [[quantum mechanics]]. They are approximately 200 [[nanometer]]s wide, the size of the smallest [[bacteria]], for which reason the discoverers have expressed hope that they might one day actually see quantum droplets.<ref name="sa"/>
