{{Infobox writer | name = Jaroslav Hašek | image = Jaroslav Hašek.gif | caption = Jaroslav Hašek in his late years | birth_date = {{birth date|1883|4|30|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Prague]], [[Austria-Hungary]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1923|1|3|1883|4|30|df=y}} | death_place = [[Lipnice nad Sázavou]], [[Czechoslovakia]] | occupation = Novelist, humorist | nationality = | genre = historical satire | notableworks = ''[[The Good Soldier Švejk]]'' | signature = Jaroslav Hašek - podpis.svg }} [[Image:Jaroslav Hasek - pomnik v Lipnici nad Sazavou - detail.jpg|thumb|upright|Monument to Jaroslav Hašek in [[Lipnice nad Sázavou]]]] '''Jaroslav Hašek''' ({{IPA-cs|ˈjaroslav ˈɦaʃɛk|lang}}; 30 April 1883 – 3 January 1923) was a [[Czechs|Czech]] writer, [[Humorism|humorist]], [[Satire|satirist]], journalist, [[Bohemianism|bohemian]] and anarchist. He is best known for his novel ''[[The Good Soldier Švejk]]'', an unfinished collection of farcical incidents about a soldier in [[World War I]] and a satire on the ineptitude of authority figures. The novel has been translated into about 60 languages, making it the most translated novel in Czech literature.
