[[Image:Duportail exb.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Louis Lebègue Duportail]]
'''Louis Lebègue de Presle Duportail'''<ref>[http://www.ushistory.org/valleyforge/served/duport.html Historic Valley Forge – General Chevalier Louis Lebègue dePresle Duportail]</ref><ref>Some sources spell his name as '''Louis Le Bèque de Presle du Portail''', with a mistaken {{angle bracket|q}} instead of a {{angle bracket|g}}.</ref> ({{IPA-fr|lwi ləbɛɡ dəpʁɛl dypɔʁtaj|lang}}; 14 May 1743 &ndash; 12 August 1802) was a French military leader who served as a volunteer and the [[Chief of Engineers|chief engineer]] in the [[Continental Army]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]]. He also served as the [[Minister of Defence (France)|French Minister of Defense]] during the beginning of the [[French Revolution]].
Duportail was born near [[Orléans]], France, in 1743. He graduated from the royal engineer school in [[Charleville-Mézières|Mézières]], France, as a qualified engineer officer in 1765. Promoted to [[lieutenant colonel]] in the Royal Corps of Engineers, Duportail was secretly sent to America in March 1777 to serve in [[George Washington|Washington's]] [[Continental Army]] under an agreement between [[Benjamin Franklin]] and the government of [[King Louis XVI]] of France. He was appointed colonel and commander of all engineers in the Continental Army, July 1777; brigadier general, November 17, 1777; commander, [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Corps of Engineers]], May 1779; and major general (Brevet), November 16, 1781.
Duportail participated in fortifications planning from [[Boston, Massachusetts]] to [[Charleston, South Carolina]], where he was captured following the surrender of the city in May 1780, and helped Washington evolve the primarily defensive military strategy that wore down the British Army. Subsequently exchanged, he also directed the construction of [[siege]] works at the [[Battle of Yorktown (1781)|Battle of Yorktown]], site of the decisive Franco-American victory of the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]]. During the encampment at [[Valley Forge]] in late-1777 and early-1778, his headquarters was at [[Cressbrook Farm]].<ref name="arch">{{cite web| url = http://www.arch.state.pa.us/| title = National Historic Landmarks & National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania| publisher = ARCH: Pennsylvania's Historic Architecture & Archaeology| format = Searchable database| accessdate = 2012-11-02}} ''Note:'' This includes {{cite web| url = https://www.dot7.state.pa.us/ce_imagery/phmc_scans/H001532_01H.pdf | title = National Register of Historic Places Inventory Nomination Form: Cressbrook Farm| accessdate = 2012-11-03| author =Pennsylvania Register of Historic Sites and Landmarks| format = PDF| date= January 1972}}</ref>
Returning to France in October 1783, Duportail became an infantry officer and in 1788 a Marechal-de-Camp (Brigadier General). He served as France's [[Minister of Defence (France)|minister of war]] from November 16, 1790, through December 7, 1791, during the beginning of the [[French Revolution]] and promoted military reforms. Forced into hiding by radical [[Jacobin Club|Jacobins]], he escaped to America and bought a farm near [[Valley Forge, Pennsylvania]]. He lived there until 1802, when he died at sea while attempting to return to France.
